 From the 1970s, there's been a concept that the CO2 buildup we're evidently witnessing is part of the climate's regular oscillation from ice age to warmth and back.<br>
<br>
I was lucky enough to find the movie in my local library.<br>
If you can watch real video, try this movie (57 minutes)<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://thule.org/iceage.html">thule.org/iceage.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
Note that the hosting website takes a different tack, by saying that this is false, and orbital variances are to blame (They also question whether we really went to the Moon...).<br>
<br>
The real effect of CO2 buildup isn't an even, global warming.  In rough chaotic interactions, pockets will develop, and pick up moisture from temperate seas. This energy leads to the chaotic weather we're seeing more of, and it'll get worse.<br>
 Eventually, the precipitation from all this dumps down, and some of it will fall in polar regions. This makes the poles colder, and reflects sunlight tending to keep it this way. In this way, moisture from equatorial oceans will go north, to fall as snow, adding to glaciers.<br>
<br>
During an ice age, glaciers grind rock into dust. This glacial loess dust gets transported globally, enriching soils with minerals. During an interglacial epoch, this mineralization gets worn down, and carried away by erosion. As this happens, plant life weakens. As plants die and forest disappear, the carbon they hold gets released.<br>
Our CO2 contribution is only hastening this, as is the man-made deforestation.<br>
<br>
During glaciation, CO2 levels peak, and during the early periods of an interglacial, CO2 is at its lowest.<br>
Tests show conclusively that mixed rock dust greatly aids plant life, from nitrogen-fixing bacteria, to worms and bugs, to the biggest trees and to little back-yard garden plots.<br>
<br>
BTW, the southern temperate and equatorial regions aren't immune. Desertification takes a horrendous toll, and long before the glaciers grow very much, food and clean water are hard to come by. Oz will have too much trouble feeding it's own shrinking &amp; starving population and daling with catastrophic chaotic weather to take in migrants.<br>
<br>
<br>
